        "content": "     1→[\n     2→  {\n     3→    \"title\": \"How I use Claude Code: Separation of Planning and Execution\",\n     4→    \"description\": \"Boris Tane shares insights from 9 months of intensive Claude Code usage. Core principle: 'Never let Claude write a single line of code before I've reviewed and approved a written plan.' Workflow cycle (1-6 iterations): Research → Planning → Annotation Iteration → Todo List → Implementation → Feedback Iteration. Separating planning from execution significantly reduces waste, helps maintain control over architectural decisions, and achieves better results with minimal tokens. The most important thing for complex tasks is investing time in upfront planning.\",\n     5→    \"author\": \"Boris Tane\",\n     6→    \"source\": \"Hacker News\",\n     7→    \"url\": \"https://boristane.com\",\n     8→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-23\",\n     9→    \"topics\": [\"Claude Code\", \"AI workflow\", \"planning\", \"execution\", \"best practices\"],\n    10→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n    11→  },\n    12→  {\n    13→    \"title\": \"Llama 3.1 70B on a Single RTX 3090 via NVMe-to-GPU Bypass\",\n    14→    \"description\": \"NTransformer project achieves running Llama 3.1 70B on a single RTX 3090 using gpu-nvme-direct technique. Uses DMA (Direct Memory Access) to stream model weights directly from NVMe storage to GPU, completely bypassing CPU. Enables running 70B parameter models on consumer-grade GPUs with limited VRAM (24GB). Significantly lowers barrier for local large model deployment. Technical innovation optimizes traditional NVMe offloading by implementing direct NVMe-to-GPU DMA transfers.\",\n    15→    \"author\": \"xaskasdf\",\n    16→    \"source\": \"Hacker News\",\n    17→    \"url\": \"https://github.com/xaskasdf\",\n    18→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-23\",\n    19→    \"topics\": [\"LLM\", \"GPU optimization\", \"local inference\", \"NVMe\", \"Llama 3.1\"],\n    20→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n    21→  },\n    22→  {\n    23→    \"title\": \"Claws are now a new layer on top of LLM agents\",\n    24→    \"description\": \"Andrej Karpathy describes Claws as a new layer above LLM agents. Quote: 'Just as LLM Agents represent a new stage in LLM development, Claws are undoubtedly another major leap forward for LLM Agents.' Claws are an AI execution system that can autonomously organize tools, complete workflows, and maintain long-term running states. Unlike LLM Agents that require manual guidance for single operations, Claws remove these limitations and enable true autonomous task execution. Karpathy bought a Mac mini specifically to experiment with Claws, sparking a buying spree in the developer community.\",\n    25→    \"author\": \"Andrej Karpathy\",\n    26→    \"source\": \"Twitter/X\",\n    27→    \"url\": \"https://twitter.com/karpathy\",\n    28→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-22\",\n    29→    \"topics\": [\"AI agents\", \"Claws\", \"LLM architecture\", \"autonomous systems\", \"OpenClaw\"],\n    30→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    31→  },\n    32→  {\n    33→    \"title\": \"zclaw: Personal AI Assistant in Under 888 KB, Running on ESP32\",\n    34→    \"description\": \"MimiClaw project demonstrates running OpenClaw on ESP32-S3 microcontroller. Size: Under 888 KB, Cost: ~$5-10 USD, Power: ~0.5W. No Operating System required - runs pure C firmware with ESP-IDF and FreeRTOS. Implements full memory system with SOUL.md (personality), USER.md (user info), MEMORY.md (long-term memory), and daily notes. Features complete ReAct Agent Loop with Claude API for thinking, tool calling, and memory management. Capabilities include multi-turn conversations, hardware control (GPIO, I2C, SPI), temperature monitoring, relay control, web search, and OTA upgrades. Available on GitHub: memovai/mimiclaw.\",\n    35→    \"author\": \"tnm\",\n    36→    \"source\": \"Hacker News\",\n    37→    \"url\": \"https://github.com/memovai/mimiclaw\",\n    38→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-22\",\n    39→    \"topics\": [\"AI agents\", \"embedded systems\", \"ESP32\", \"OpenClaw\", \"edge AI\"],\n    40→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n    41→  },\n    42→  {\n    43→    \"title\": \"a16z Partner Says 'Vibe Code' Theory is Wrong\",\n    44→    \"description\": \"Martin Casado, a16z general partner, challenges 'vibe coding' approach while expressing optimism about AI's impact on software engineering. Critics argue vibe coding creates 'trust debt' where senior engineers must reverse-engineer AI-generated code. Real-world failures include binary search implementations that failed under specific inputs, authentication systems that collapsed with complex features, and maintenance nightmares described as 'archaeology.' METR study found experienced developers using AI tools were 19% slower than those not using them. Core issue: problems only become apparent after system failures, creating undebbuggable, hard-to-extend, and painful-to-maintain production systems.\",\n    45→    \"author\": \"Martin Casado\",\n    46→    \"source\": \"Hacker News\",\n    47→    \"url\": \"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=41006865\",\n    48→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-22\",\n    49→    \"topics\": [\"vibe coding\", \"AI coding\", \"code quality\", \"software engineering\", \"a16z\"],\n    50→    \"type\": \"discussion\"\n    51→  },\n    52→  {\n    53→    \"title\": \"Claude Code Founder Predicts Plan Mode May Become History\",\n    54→    \"description\": \"Claude Code founder Boris Cherny predicts that Plan Mode may become history as AI becomes smart enough to automatically decide when to plan vs. execute. The AI is reaching a point where it can autonomously determine the optimal approach without manual mode switching. This evolution reflects broader trend in AI coding tools: moving from explicit user control to intelligent, context-aware assistance. Highlights the rapid advancement of AI coding capabilities in early 2026.\",\n    55→    \"author\": \"Boris Cherny\",\n    56→    \"source\": \"Tech Media\",\n    57→    \"url\": \"https://m.itbear.com.cn/html/2026-02/1158959.html\",\n    58→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-21\",\n    59→    \"topics\": [\"Claude Code\", \"Plan Mode\", \"AI evolution\", \"autonomous coding\", \"workflow automation\"],\n    60→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    61→  },\n    62→  {\n    63→    \"title\": \"2026 GitHub Trending: AI Agents Explode, Traditional Languages Fade\",\n    64→    \"description\": \"GitHub 2026 trending analysis shows dramatic shift: TypeScript emerges as biggest winner, AI Agent projects see explosive growth. Top emerging tools: OpenClaw (potentially standard for personal AI), Superpowers/MCP (integration hub), Shannon and Pi-mono (core infrastructure). Declining trends: New programming languages (Zig, Mojo, Gleam) nearly disappeared from trending, traditional frontend frameworks (Next.js, Svelte, Astro) seeing significantly less interest, self-hosted tools (unless AI-related) experiencing sharp decline. 2026 called 'Year of Agent Engineering' - focus shifted from 'which model is strongest' to 'which Agent framework is most practical, engineered, and composable.' Skills-based architecture emerging: composable skill components similar to frontend UI component libraries.\",\n    65→    \"author\": \"GitHub Analysis\",\n    66→    \"source\": \"Tech Blog\",\n    67→    \"url\": \"https://www.cnblogs.com/YahuiWang/p/19631223\",\n    68→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-20\",\n    69→    \"topics\": [\"GitHub trending\", \"AI agents\", \"developer tools\", \"ecosystem shifts\", \"skills architecture\"],\n    70→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n    71→  },\n    72→  {\n    73→    \"title\": \"NanoClaw: 4000 Lines of Code for Safe, Efficient AI Execution Hub\",\n    74→    \"description\": \"Andrej Karpathy recommends NanoClaw, a lightweight AI execution system with core code of only 4000 lines. Designed as an AI execution hub that can autonomously organize tools, complete workflows, and maintain long-term running states. Part of broader OpenClaw ecosystem that includes various lightweight AI assistants (OpenClaw, PicoClaw, NanoClaw, MimiClaw). Represents trend toward minimal, efficient AI agent infrastructure that can run on resource-constrained hardware. Karpathy's endorsement sparked developer interest and experimentation with Mac mini deployments.\",\n    75→    \"author\": \"Andrej Karpathy\",\n    76→    \"source\": \"Tech Media\",\n    77→    \"url\": \"https://m.itbear.com.cn/html/2026-02/1160776.html\",\n    78→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-20\",\n    79→    \"topics\": [\"NanoClaw\", \"AI agents\", \"lightweight infrastructure\", \"OpenClaw ecosystem\", \"Karpathy\"],\n    80→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n    81→  },\n    82→  {\n    83→    \"title\": \"AI Coding Tools February 2026: Claude Opus 4.6 vs GPT-5.3-Codex\",\n    84→    \"description\": \"Major model releases in February 2026: Claude Opus 4.6 (Anthropic) with 400K context window, Agent Teams functionality for parallel task coordination, discovered 500+ high-risk vulnerabilities in open-source libraries, pricing $5/$25 per million tokens. GPT-5.3-Codex (OpenAI) with 25% speed improvement, new SWE-Bench Pro benchmark records, OpenAI Frontier platform for enterprise system integration. Gemini 3.1 Pro (Google) with 1M-2M+ context window, MMLU accuracy of 95.1% surpassing human expert average. Developer reports show 10x speed improvement for complex tasks. AI coding tools transitioning from experimental assistants to essential development partners.\",\n    85→    \"author\": \"Industry News\",\n    86→    \"source\": \"Tech Media\",\n    87→    \"url\": \"https://www.donews.com/news/detail/8/6394371.html\",\n    88→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-19\",\n    89→    \"topics\": [\"Claude Opus 4.6\", \"GPT-5.3-Codex\", \"AI coding\", \"model comparison\", \"benchmark competition\"],\n    90→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n    91→  },\n    92→  {\n    93→    \"title\": \"Vibe Coding Era Ends, Agentic Engineering Era Begins\",\n    94→    \"description\": \"Andrej Karpathy announces the end of Vibe Coding era and the beginning of Agentic Engineering. Evolution from intuition-based programming to more rigorous, precise AI-assisted programming methods. Timeline: November 2025: 80% manual coding + 20% AI; December 2025: 80% AI agents + 20% manual editing/refinement. Claude and Codex crossed consistency/coherence thresholds in late 2025, making AI-first coding suddenly viable. Represents fundamental shift in how developers approach AI-assisted programming - from casual 'vibes' to structured agent engineering.\",\n    95→    \"author\": \"Andrej Karpathy\",\n    96→    \"source\": \"Twitter/X\",\n    97→    \"url\": \"https://m.toutiao.com/article/7603373016365482530/\",\n    98→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-18\",\n    99→    \"topics\": [\"Vibe Coding\", \"Agentic Engineering\", \"paradigm shift\", \"AI coding\", \"Claude\"],\n   100→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   101→  },\n   102→  {\n   103→    \"title\": \"LLMs Changing Software Development Constraints: Golden Age for Programming Language Research\",\n   104→    \"description\": \"Andrej Karpathy observes that for programming language and formal methods researchers, this is the most exciting time because LLMs are changing the constraints of software development. Insight: 'Agents know what an App is, Grandma doesn't need to.' Mentions nanochat project: 'Best $100 chat tool you can get' with 43,475 GitHub stars. Highlights how AI agents are abstracting away complexity, making software development more accessible while creating new opportunities for language and tool designers.\",\n   105→    \"author\": \"Andrej Karpathy\",\n   106→    \"source\": \"Twitter/X\",\n   107→    \"url\": \"https://x.com/karpathy/status/2024583544157458452\",\n   108→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-18\",\n   109→    \"topics\": [\"programming languages\", \"LLM constraints\", \"AI agents\", \"nanochat\", \"software development\"],\n   110→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   111→  },\n   112→  {\n   113→    \"title\": \"AI Coding Ecosystem February 2026: Market Dynamics and Enterprise Adoption\",\n   114→    \"description\": \"2026 AI coding tools market analysis: Claude Code Opus 4.6 with Agent Teams (multi-instance parallel coordination) and 1M token context window, pricing $20-$200/month. Cursor 2.3+Composer 1.5 model introduces Shadow Workspace for background prediction and Plan Mode for design-first workflow, valued at $2.93B, $200M ARR. Copilot maintains 68% market share but limited context window. Windsurf supports 1M line codebase remote indexing. Trends: multi-agent coordination becoming standard, context windows dramatically expanding, Chinese enterprise alternatives (Baidu Qianfan, Moore Threads) emerging. Market shifting from 'AI assistant' to truly autonomous 'AI Agent' capable of planning, executing, and coordinating complex development tasks.\",\n   115→    \"author\": \"Tech Media\",\n   116→    \"source\": \"Technical Analysis\",\n   117→    \"url\": \"https://juejin.cn/post/7602259669730541595\",\n   118→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-19\",\n   119→    \"topics\": [\"AI coding tools\", \"Claude Code\", \"Cursor\", \"market analysis\", \"multi-agent\", \"enterprise adoption\"],\n   120→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   121→  },\n   122→  {\n   123→    \"title\": \"Claude Code Father vs Karpathy: Programming is Dead, Keyboards Gathering Dust\",\n   124→    \"description\": \"Conversation between Andrej Karpathy and Claude Code's Boris Cherny about how 20 years of programming workflow was disrupted in weeks: 80% of code now written by AI. 2026 predictions: dual evolution in model layer and Agent layer creating 'product effect' through multiplication rather than addition. Warning about 'Slopacolypse' risk: codebases may be flooded with AI-generated code that appears correct but has problems. Programmers evolving from 'code writers' to 'architects' and 'reviewers.' Highlights both opportunities and risks of AI-first development.\",\n   125→    \"author\": \"Andrej Karpathy, Boris Cherny\",\n   126→    \"source\": \"Podcast/Discussion\",\n   127→    \"url\": \"https://m.163.com/dy/article/KKU06RJI0551ABV6.html\",\n   128→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-17\",\n   129→    \"topics\": [\"AI coding\", \"Claude Code\", \"programming workflow\", \"code quality\", \"career evolution\"],\n   130→    \"type\": \"discussion\"\n   131→  },\n   132→  {\n   133→    \"title\": \"2026 AI Agent Development Tools Ecosystem Panorama\",\n   134→    \"description\": \"Comprehensive analysis of 2026 AI Agent development tools ecosystem. Market evolution from 'AI assistant' to truly autonomous 'AI Agent' capable of planning, executing, and coordinating complex development tasks. Tool specialization trends: Claude Code CLI for minimal terminal scenarios, Cursor excels at project understanding and multi-file editing, OpenClaw focuses on long-term memory tasks. API aggregation platforms emerging to avoid multiple $20 subscriptions. Multi-agent coordination becoming standard. Chinese enterprise solutions (Baidu Qianfan Coding Plan, Moore Threads AI Coding Plan) providing localized alternatives. Ecosystem maturity improving: enterprise features (security, collaboration, billing) becoming standard.\",\n   135→    \"author\": \"Developer Community\",\n   136→    \"source\": \"Technical Blog\",\n   137→    \"url\": \"https://juejin.cn/post/7608178484015382568\",\n   138→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-17\",\n   139→    \"topics\": [\"AI agents\", \"development tools\", \"ecosystem analysis\", \"enterprise features\", \"Chinese alternatives\"],\n   140→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   141→  },\n   142→  {\n   143→    \"title\": \"Amjad Masad: From 'How' to 'What' Paradigm Shift in AI Coding\",\n   144→    \"description\": \"Replit CEO Amjad Masad articulates next stage of AI Agent evolution: shifting from 'telling AI how to do things' to 'telling AI what to do,' letting AI figure out execution path autonomously. Replit already has projects achieving zero human involvement from goal receipt to multi-agent collaboration to code deployment. Predicts AI Agent code generation, testing, and deployment speed growing 3.4x per quarter, approaching human developer limits. Expects human programming roles to potentially decline within ~2 years (early 2027). Future IDE will be task receiving, scheduling, and output interface system, not code editor.\",\n   145→    \"author\": \"Amjad Masad\",\n   146→    \"source\": \"Interview\",\n   147→    \"url\": \"https://ishare.ifeng.com/c/s/v002eum5fCXBMVm-_4O8x24UR-_N8BAIBvsiF3sqhMnZtMid0__\",\n   148→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-15\",\n   149→    \"topics\": [\"AI agents\", \"Replit\", \"paradigm shift\", \"code generation\", \"developer evolution\"],\n   150→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   151→  },\n   152→  {\n   153→    \"title\": \"Simon Willison's 6 AI Predictions: 1 Year Agents, 3 Years Pulitzer, 6 Years Crisis\",\n   154→    \"description\": \"Simon Willison's 6 major AI predictions: Within 1 year AI Agents will see practical application; within 3 years someone will win Pulitzer Prize using GenAI tools, journalists will use LLMs to process data; within 6 years AI will simplify art creation but if AGI replaces many human jobs it may trigger social crisis. His LLM command-line tool integrated into Kali Linux 2025.3 as 'llm-tools-nmap' experimental plugin. Highlights both opportunities and risks of AI advancement.\",\n   155→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison\",\n   156→    \"source\": \"Technical Blog\",\n   157→    \"url\": \"https://segmentfault.com/a/1190000046630992\",\n   158→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-14\",\n   159→    \"topics\": [\"AI agents\", \"Pulitzer Prize\", \"AGI risks\", \"LLM tools\", \"Kali Linux\"],\n   160→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   161→  },\n   162→  {\n   163→    \"title\": \"Programming Dead? 2026 AI Technology Trends Predictions\",\n   164→    \"description\": \"Django co-founder Simon Willison's 2026 AI predictions: Within 1 year (late 2026), LLM-generated code quality will be 'undeniably excellent,' view that AI-generated code is garbage will become untenable, human manual coding proportion drops to single-digit percentages. Within 3 years: AI will be able to collaboratively develop browsers. Within 6 years: hand-written code may become history, programmers shift to architecture design and AI collaboration. Core themes: security issues (sandbox solutions), Jevons paradox, programmer role transformation. Represents optimistic but measured view of AI's impact on software development.\",\n   165→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison\",\n   166→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n   167→    \"url\": \"https://developer.aliyun.com/article/1712150\",\n   168→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-13\",\n   169→    \"topics\": [\"AI predictions\", \"code generation\", \"programming future\", \"LLM quality\", \"developer evolution\"],\n   170→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   171→  },\n   172→  {\n   173→    \"title\": \"AgentCgroup Research: First Systematic Analysis of AI Agent Resource Management\",\n   174→    \"description\": \"February 2026 arXiv paper presents first systematic study of AI agent resource dynamics. Key findings: tool calling accounts for 56-74% of latency, memory is primary bottleneck (not CPU), peak-to-average memory fluctuation reaches 15.4x. Reveals AI agent resource consumption patterns are fundamentally different from traditional applications, requiring new resource management and scheduling strategies. Important guidance for multi-agent system deployment in production environments. Addresses critical infrastructure challenges as AI agents move from experimental to production use.\",\n   175→    \"author\": \"Research Community\",\n   176→    \"source\": \"ArXiv Paper\",\n   177→    \"url\": \"https://arxiv.org/html/2602.09345v1\",\n   178→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-10\",\n   179→    \"topics\": [\"AI agents\", \"resource management\", \"memory optimization\", \"latency analysis\", \"multi-agent systems\"],\n   180→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   181→  },\n   182→  {\n   183→    \"title\": \"OpenAI vs Anthropic Same-Day Showdown: GPT-5.3-Codex vs Claude Opus 4.6\",\n   184→    \"description\": \"February 6, OpenAI and Anthropic released major coding models 20 minutes apart. OpenAI launched GPT-5.3-Codex with 25% speed improvement, integrated into Cursor/GitHub/VS Code, released macOS app, using Codex to build Codex achieving recursive AI development. Anthropic released Claude Opus 4.6 with Agent Teams functionality for task segmentation and parallel coordination, discovered 500+ high-risk security vulnerabilities, pricing $5/$25 per million tokens. Benchmarks: GPT-5.3-Codex sets records on SWE-Bench Pro, Claude Opus 4.6 leads on MRCR v2 and GDPval-AA. Developer reports show 10x speed improvement for complex tasks. Traditional security stocks fell (CrowdStrike down 6%). AI coding tools transitioning from experimental assistants to essential development partners.\",\n   185→    \"author\": \"Industry News\",\n   186→    \"source\": \"Tech Media\",\n   187→    \"url\": \"https://www.donews.com/news/detail/8/6394371.html\",\n   188→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-06\",\n   189→    \"topics\": [\"OpenAI\", \"Anthropic\", \"GPT-5.3-Codex\", \"Claude Opus 4.6\", \"benchmark competition\", \"AI coding\"],\n   190→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   191→  },\n   192→  {\n   193→    \"title\": \"Lex Fridman Podcast #490: 2026 AI State of the Art Comprehensive Report\",\n   194→    \"description\": \"4-hour super-long interview with guests Sebastian Raschka and Nathan Lambert. Covers: China-US AI competition, ChatGPT vs Claude vs Gemini vs Grok comparison, AI coding tools (Claude Code and Cursor), open-source vs closed-source LLMs, Transformer architecture evolution, Scaling Laws validity, AI training pipeline (pre-training/mid-training/post-training), post-training new techniques, career advice, AI industry 72+ hour work culture, text diffusion models, tool use and agents, continual learning, long context, robotics, AGI timeline (predicting human-level by 2030), future of programming jobs, business models, future of OpenAI/Anthropic/Google DeepMind/xAI/Meta, GPU computing and NVIDIA. Comprehensive overview of AI landscape in early 2026.\",\n   195→    \"author\": \"Lex Fridman, Sebastian Raschka, Nathan Lambert\",\n   196→    \"source\": \"Podcast\",\n   197→    \"url\": \"https://www.bilibili.com/video/BV1bqFPzCEHz/\",\n   198→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-01\",\n   199→    \"topics\": [\"AI state of the art\", \"LLM comparison\", \"AI coding\", \"open source models\", \"AGI predictions\", \"Scaling Laws\", \"agents\"],\n   200→    \"type\": \"discussion\"\n   201→  }\n   202→]\n   203→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"
      }
